[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34m/*\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mTwo RexxText values are considered equal if their extended grapheme clusters\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mare canonically equivalent.This is used by the Swift language.\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mQ&A: https://lists.isocpp.org/sg16/2018/08/0121.php\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34m\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mTODO: confirm that it's NFC, and only that.\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mThe definition of canonical equivalence by the Unicode standard seems not\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mlimited to NFC. https://unicode.org/notes/tn5/\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34m*/\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[11.778, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34m"]
[0.000, "o", "/*\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mThe strict comparison operators use the NFC normalization.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mAfter normalization, they delegate to the String's strict comparison operators.\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mThe non-strict comparison operators use the NFKD normalization plus\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34m    stripIgnorable:.true\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34m    lump:.true"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mAfter normalization + transformations, they delegate to the String's non-strict"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mcomparison operators. Thanks to the lump transformation, all the Unicode spaces\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mare supported.\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34m*/\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "ooRexx[bash]> \u001b[1;35mte"]
